🟠 Medium — RF Resolution Lost on Server-Triggered Factory Reset
gprs_core.ino line 513 — The server DELETE_DATA command preserves station.doc, station.txt, and rf_fw.txt, but not rf_res.txt. The LCD factory reset (lcdkeypad.ino line 782) preserves all four, including rf_res.txt. If an operator set resolution to 0.25mm and a remote server DELETE_DATA is issued, rf_res.txt is deleted. On next boot, both rf_fw.txt (preserved, still equals DEFAULT_RF_RESOLUTION) and the rebuilt rf_res.txt reset to DEFAULT_RF_RESOLUTION = 0.50. All subsequent rainfall is double-counted silently. Fix: add "/rf_res.txt" to the preserve list in gprs_core.ino at line 513.

🟡 Low — RF Resolution Accepts Corrupted Zero from SPIFFS
AIO9_5.0.ino line 866 — user_res = f.readString().toFloat() produces 0.0 if rf_res.txt is partially written (power-cut during save). When last_fw_res == DEFAULT_RF_RESOLUTION (no firmware change), active_res = user_res = 0.0 → RF_RESOLUTION = 0.0 → all rainfall permanently reads zero. Fix: add if (user_res < 0.1f) user_res = DEFAULT_RF_RESOLUTION; after the file read.

🟡 Low — diag_backlog_total Never Reset
RTC_DATA_ATTR int diag_backlog_total accumulates indefinitely but overflows at ~61,000 years worst case. Not functionally dangerous, but the value shown in health reports after a long deployment will be unbounded. Harmless in practice.

